===Chicago Bears===
Vereen was drafted in the fourth round (131st overall) of the [[2014 NFL Draft]] by the [[Chicago Bears]]. He signed a 4-year deal with the Bears on May 12, 2014. Vereen and fellow draft class quarterback [[David Fales]] were the NFL's first two draft picks to agree to terms.<ref>http://www.chicagobears.com/news/article-1/Vereen-Fales-agree-to-4-year-deals/5d89fd4f-3797-4aa0-a4bf-4242fe782bba</ref>  

He was released by the Bears on September 29, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN.com|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago-bears/post/_/id/4700174/bears-waive-former-4th-round-pick-brock-vereen|title=Bears waive former fourth-round pick Brock Vereen|first=Jeff|last=Dickerson|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>

===Minnesota Vikings===
Vereen was signed to the [[Minnesota Vikings]] practice squad on October 1, 2015 after being unclaimed on waivers.<ref>{{cite news|work=NBCSports.com|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/10/01/brock-vereen-lands-on-minnesotas-practice-squad/|title=Brock Vereen lands on Minnesota’s practice squad|first=Mike|last=Florio|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> He was waived by the Vikings on November 13.<ref>{{cite web|work=Vikings.com|url=http://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Vikings-Sign-Chase-Ford-to-Practice-Squad-Release-Brock-Vereen/cdad6a8c-dcd4-4dbb-b7ea-9af48b5d7adb|title=Vikings Sign Chase Ford to Practice Squad, Release Brock Vereen|date=November 13, 2015|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref>

===New England Patriots===
The [[New England Patriots]] signed Vereen to their practice squad on November 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|work=NBCSports.com|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/11/18/patriots-add-joseph-fauria-brock-vereen-to-practice-squad/|title=Patriots add Joseph Fauria, Brock Vereen to practice squad|first=Josh|last=Alper|date=November 18, 2015|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> On January 26, 2016, Vereen signed a futures contract with the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Patriots officially announce signing of eight to future contracts|url = http://itiswhatitis.weei.com/sports/newengland/football/patriots/2016/01/26/patriots-officially-announce-signing-of-eight-to-futures-contracts/|website = It Is What It Is|access-date = January 27, 2016|language = en-US}}</ref>

On August 15, 2016, Vereen announced his retirement after only two years in the NFL. However, two days later, he was reinstated. Upon his return, the New England Patriots released Vereen.

===Kansas City Chiefs===
On August 17, 2016, Vereen was claimed off waivers by the Chiefs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs claim Brock Vereen on waivers|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/17/chiefs-claim-brock-vereen-on-waivers/|last=Florio|first=Mike|website=NBCSports.com}}</ref> On September 3, 2016, he was released by the Chiefs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs Down to NFL Mandated Roster Limit|url=http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Down-to-NFL-Mandated-Roster-Limit/eaa26747-962f-4a0c-a143-502c64f318ed|website=Chiefs.com|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013185227/http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Down-to-NFL-Mandated-Roster-Limit/eaa26747-962f-4a0c-a143-502c64f318ed|archive-date=October 13, 2016|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> The next day, he was signed to the Chiefs' practice squad.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs Announce Additional Roster Moves|url=http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Announce-Additional-Roster-Moves/c8725899-0072-426f-b271-3f07240af7a3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126161600/http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Announce-Additional-Roster-Moves/c8725899-0072-426f-b271-3f07240af7a3|dead-url=yes|archive-date=November 26, 2017|website=Chiefs.com|date=September 4, 2016}}</ref> He was released from the practice squad two days later.

==Personal life==
His father, Henry Vereen, was a ninth round pick of the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in the [[1979 NFL Draft]],<ref name="New England Patriots: Shane Vereen">{{cite web|title=New England Patriots: Shane Vereen|url=http://www.patriots.com/team/roster/Shane-Vereen/13170676-4b53-4249-b38b-9fb4f74b904c|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023172924/http://www.patriots.com/team/roster/Shane-Vereen/13170676-4b53-4249-b38b-9fb4f74b904c|archive-date=October 23, 2012|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> and played wide receiver in the [[Canadian Football League]] for the [[BC Lions]] in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Powerful Lions improve lineup|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iUYwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rKUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4532,3824406&dq=henry+vereen&hl=en|accessdate=October 23, 2012|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=June 30, 1984}}</ref> Vereen is a first cousin once removed of stage actor and dancer [[Ben Vereen]].<ref name="Boston">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/extra_points/2011/04/patriots_select_6.html|title=Patriots select RB Shane Vereen with the 56th pick|first=Zuri|last=Berry|date=April 29, 2011|publisher=[[The New York Times Company|NY Times Co.]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> His brother, [[Shane Vereen]], was a second-round pick of the [[New England Patriots]] in the [[2011 NFL Draft]].<ref>[http://msn.foxsports.com/north/story/brock-vereen-hopes-to-follow-in-his-brother-s-nfl-footsteps-122313 Brock Vereen hopes to follow in his brother's NFL footsteps]</ref><ref>[http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/118104/brock-vereen-follows-brothers-footsteps Brock Vereen follows brother's footsteps]</ref><ref>[http://www.twincities.com/gophersfootball/ci_21345205/gophers-football-sibling-rivalry-has-been-driving-force Gophers football: Sibling rivalry has been a driving force for safety Brock Vereen]</ref>

